%N A307111 a(n) is the least primitive n-abundant number k with the largest possible abundancy index sigma(k)/k.
%C A307111 A primitive n-abundant number k is a number with sigma(k)/k > n and sigma(d)/d < n for all the proper divisors d of k.
%C A307111 Cohen proved that for any given eps > 0 there are only finitely many primitive n-abundant numbers k with sigma(k)/k >= n + eps. Thus for each n there is a maximal value of the abundancy index sigma(k)/k for primitive n-abundant numbers k. If this maximum occurs at more than one number the least of them is given in this sequence.
%C A307111 The calculated terms (currently to a(16)) each divide a term of A137825 to give 1, a prime or a semiprime. The construction of A137825 gives reason to expect that we should find each a(n) here by dividing out a small number of prime factors from a term of A137825 with suitably greater abundancy than n, but not necessarily as small a number of factors as 2. This nevertheless suggests an efficient calculation strategy given that when a strong candidate for a(n) is found it is easy to verify that it cannot be beaten by one that is not a divisor of a specific A137825(k) by using the relationship in my like dated comment in A137825. - _Peter Munn_, May 01 2026
%H A307111 Peter Munn, <a href="/A307111/b307111.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..13</a>
%H A307111 Graeme L. Cohen, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/S0025-5718-1984-0744936-X ">Primitive alpha-abundant numbers</a>, Mathematics of Computation, Vol. 43, No. 167 (1984), pp. 263-270.
%H A307111 Peter Munn, <a href="/A307111/a307111_1.txt">PARI program (term checker)</a>.
%H A307111 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Abundancy.html">Abundancy</a>.
%e A307111 3465 is in the sequence since it is the primitive abundant (A071395) number with the largest possible abundancy index among the primitive abundant numbers: sigma(3465)/3465 = 832/385 = 2.161003...
%e A307111 The abundancy indices of the next terms are 1248/385 = 3.241558..., 193536/46189 = 4.190088..., 642816/124729 = 5.153701...
%e A307111 a(6) = A137825(20)/23 = 4709794079401210800/23 = 204773655626139600 has abundancy c = 2559836160/418065479 > 6 and is primitive 6-abundant since A395192(204773655626139600) has abundancy < 6. A search determines that all other primitive 6-abundant divisors of A137825(21) have abundancy less than c. Since c > 6 * abundancy (A137825(22))/abundancy(A137825(21)) = 6 * 54/53 we can use the relationship in the May 01 2026 comment in A137825 to prove that a nondivisor of A137825(21) that is a primitive 6-abundant number has abundancy less than c.
